# Copy to .env and fill in. Only .env.example is committed.

# ─── Supabase ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co
VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-key-here

# ─── Multi-tenancy — which hotel this deployment serves ───────────────────────
# One deployment = one hotel. Both are the SAME slug from the `tenants` table;
# they exist separately because one is public (browser) and one is a boundary.
#
#   VITE_TENANT_SLUG — inlined into the bundle. Sent as the x-tenant-slug header
#     to scope PUBLIC anon reads (room types, rates, published reviews). A hint
#     only, spoofable by design — it can surface just another hotel's brochure.
#
#   TENANT_SLUG — server only, no VITE_ prefix. Authoritative: decides which
#     hotel a new profile is filed under at first SSO login. Never from client.
#
# Leave BOTH unset on a single-hotel install — the database falls back to the
# sole tenant and fails closed the moment a second hotel is added.
# VITE_TENANT_SLUG=gostay
# TENANT_SLUG=gostay

# ─── Ventera SSO — public (inlined into the browser bundle) ───────────────────
VITE_SSO_ISSUER=https://sso.ventera.ai
VITE_SSO_CLIENT_ID=gostay

# ─── Ventera SSO — server only ────────────────────────────────────────────────
# No VITE_ prefix, so Vite never inlines these into client code. Read by the
# token exchange in api/sso/token.ts (and the matching Vite dev middleware).
# On Vercel, set them as Environment Variables — not here.
SSO_ISSUER=https://sso.ventera.ai
SSO_CLIENT_ID=gostay
SSO_CLIENT_SECRET=your-client-secret-here
# Optional: extra origins allowed to run a token exchange, comma-separated.
# localhost and *.vercel.app are always allowed.
# SSO_ALLOWED_ORIGINS=https://gostay.example.com

# Optional: the role a NEW profile is created with on first web sign-in. The web
# login is the staff entrance (guests arrive via WhatsApp as 'customer'), so this
# defaults to 'staff'. Set to 'customer' if your web login is also open to guests.
# It only stamps the initial row; profiles.role in the database stays the source
# of truth afterwards — an admin can re-decide it via User Management.
# SSO_SIGNUP_ROLE=staff

# ─── Supabase identity bridge — server only ──────────────────────────────────
# Without these the browser talks to Supabase as anon, auth.uid() is NULL and
# every RLS policy denies. Sign-in still works; the app just reads public data.
#
# SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET: Supabase Dashboard > Settings > API > JWT Secret.
#   Used to sign the token that carries the SSO identity into Postgres.
# SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY: same page. Bypasses RLS — server only, never VITE_.
#   Used solely to create a user's profiles row on first login.
# SUPABASE_URL: defaults to VITE_SUPABASE_URL when unset.
SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET=your-supabase-jwt-secret
SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY=your-service-role-key
# SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co

# profiles.id is uuid_v5(this namespace, sso_sub). CHANGING IT REMAPS EVERY
# USER and orphans their bookings, chats and audit rows. Leave unset.
# SSO_UUID_NAMESPACE=b9c1a7d4-3e52-4f68-9a0b-7d2c5e814f36

# ─── WhatsApp AI booking — server only ───────────────────────────────────────
# Read by the WA webhook (api/wa/*, api/_lib/wa/*), a Vercel Node function. No
# VITE_ prefix — none of these may ever reach the browser bundle. On Vercel, set
# them as Environment Variables, not here.
#
# SSO_VENTERA_PROVISION_URL + PROVISION_API_KEY: mint a guest an SSO account by
#   phone, no browser. The webhook POSTs {phone,displayName?} to
#   <SSO_VENTERA_PROVISION_URL>/api/admin/users/provision with
#   `Authorization: Bearer <PROVISION_API_KEY>`; Ventera returns { ok, sub }.
#   Same value as Ventera's own PROVISION_API_KEY. A boundary secret — leaking it
#   lets anyone mint accounts, so treat it like the service-role key.
# SSO_VENTERA_PROVISION_URL=https://sso.ventera.ai
# PROVISION_API_KEY=your-ventera-provision-key

# ─── WhatsApp gateway (wa-ventera) — inbound webhook, server only ────────────
# WA_WEBHOOK_SECRET: the shared secret wa-ventera sends in the `x-webhook-secret`
#   header when it POSTs inbound messages to <this app>/api/wa/inbound. The route
#   rejects any request whose header does not match (constant-time). Must equal
#   the `secret` in this hotel's WEBHOOK_ROUTES entry on the gateway. No VITE_
#   prefix. When unset, the webhook denies every caller (fails closed).
# WA_WEBHOOK_SECRET=your-inbound-webhook-secret
#
# ─── WhatsApp gateway (wa-ventera) — outbound send, server only ──────────────
# No VITE_ prefix, so Vite never inlines these into client code. Read by the
# outbound helper api/_lib/wa/send.ts to reply to a guest through the gateway.
# On Vercel, set them as Environment Variables — not here.
#
# WA_VENTERA_BASE_URL: base URL of the wa-ventera gateway. The helper POSTs to
#   <base>/api/sessions/<sessionId>/send. A trailing slash is trimmed.
# WA_VENTERA_INT_KEY: integration key (an `int_*` value) sent as
#   `Authorization: Bearer <key>`. Its owner MUST be an owner/admin of the
#   target hotel session, or the gateway answers 401/403. NEVER commit a real
#   key and never give it a VITE_ prefix. When either var is unset the helper
#   returns { ok:false, error:"send_not_configured" } instead of sending.
# WA_VENTERA_BASE_URL=https://wa.ventera.ai
# WA_VENTERA_INT_KEY=int_your-integration-key-here

# ─── WhatsApp AI booking — server only ───────────────────────────────────────
# OPENAI_API_KEY: used by api/_lib/wa/ai.ts to extract booking intent + slots
#   from a guest's WhatsApp message (model gpt-4o-mini). No VITE_ prefix — it
#   must never reach the browser bundle. When UNSET, extraction still works via a
#   deterministic regex/keyword fallback (lower confidence), so this is optional.
# OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...
# OPENAI_API_URL: overrides the chat-completions endpoint. Leave unset in
#   production (defaults to https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions); it
#   exists so tests can point extraction at a local mock server.
# OPENAI_API_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions

# ─── Granting the first admin (one-time) ─────────────────────────────────────
# Roles live in profiles.role, not in this file and not in the SSO. Everyone who
# signs in gets 'customer' by default, and only an admin may promote anyone
# ("Admin can update any profile" in 002_rls_policies.sql) — so the first admin
# has to be made once, by hand, or nobody can ever grant anyone anything.
#
# Sign in once so your profile row exists, then run this in the Supabase SQL
# editor (it runs as the table owner and bypasses RLS):
#
#   update profiles set role = 'admin' where email = 'you@ventera.ai';
#
# After that, promote and demote everyone else from User Management.
